[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1818 Illinois lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on September 17, 1818, in order to elect the first lieutenant governor of Illinois upon Illinois acquiring statehood on December 3, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republican candidate Pierre Menard defeated fellow Democratic-Republican candidates William L.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] On election day, September 17, 1818, Democratic-Republican candidate Pierre Menard won the election by a margin of 1,219 votes against his foremost opponent and fellow Democratic-Republican candidate William L.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Reynolds, thereby gaining Democratic-Republican control over the office of lieutenant governor.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-illinois-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Menard was sworn in as the 1st lieutenant governor of Illinois on October 6, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois] Illinois elected its new member sometime in 1818, after gaining statehood.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] The **1818–19 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1818 and 1819, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 3.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] The Democratic-Republican Party gained two seats.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] The Federalists had only three seats being contested, of which they lost two and the third was left vacant due to a failure to elect.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] In these special elections, the winners were seated during 1818 or before March 4, 1819; ordered by election date.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] In these general elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1819 (except where noted due to late election); ordered by state.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] All of the elections involved the Class 3 seats.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] In these special elections, the winners were seated in 1819 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] The new Congress was seated December 6, 1819, so some of these late-elected senators were seated after that.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] Due to both the Class 3 seat falling vacant at the normal end of the term and the Class 1 seat falling vacant due to the death of Alexander Contee Hanson, the legislature voted for both seats simultaneously.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] Edward Lloyd received the most votes and won the Class 3 seat.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1818-united-states-senate-elections-in-illinois] William Pinkney received the second-most votes and won the Class 1 seat.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The **1818–19 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 26, 1818, and August 12, 1819.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 16th United States Congress convened on December 6, 1819.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] They occurred during President James Monroe's first term.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Also, newly admitted Alabama elected its first representatives in September 1819, increasing the size of the House to 186 seats.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] This election occurred in a politically uneventful period marked by exceptionally low levels of partisan rivalry known as the Era of Good Feelings.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The weak Federalist Party, with limited influence in few states, no longer effectively opposed the Democratic-Republican Party, which increased its large majority.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Illinois was admitted in 1818, adding one seat.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Alabama and Maine were admitted during the 16th Congress.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] One new seat was added for Alabama, while Maine, splitting from Massachusetts, simply retained its Representatives.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] There were special elections in 1818 and 1819 to the 15th United States Congress and 16th United States Congress.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Special elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Connecticut elected its members September 21, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The delegation changed from seven Federalists to seven Democratic-Republicans then the retirement of six incumbents and the party-change of the seventh.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Delaware elected its members October 5, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Georgia elected its members October 5, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Illinois elected its member August 2, 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The incumbent had just been elected to the new seat in late 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Indiana re-elected its member August 3, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Kentucky elected its members August 3, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Louisiana elected its member July 6–8, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Louisiana held an election for the 16th Congress at the same time that it held a special election to finish the 15th Congress.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Data were only available for the special election, but the general election would presumably have had very similar results, and so the results for the special election are duplicated here.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Maryland elected its members October 5, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Massachusetts elected its members November 2, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Massachusetts's electoral law required a majority for election, n Massachusetts's electoral law required a majority for electionMassachusetts's electoral law required a majority for electionecessitating additional elections in five districts on April 5, 1819, and July 26, 1819.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] This was the last election in which the District of Maine — comprising congressional districts 14 through 20 — was part of Massachusetts.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The District became the State of Maine during the 16th Congress.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] District numbers differed between source used and elsewhere on Wikipedia; district numbers used elsewhere on Wikipedia used here.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Mississippi elected its member August 2–3, 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] New Hampshire elected its members March 9, 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] New Jersey elected its members October 13, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] New York elected its members April 28–30, 1818, the earliest of any state.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] At this time, the Democratic-Republicans in New York were divided into two factions, the "Bucktails" who were opposed to Governor Dewitt Clinton's Erie Canal project, led by Martin Van Buren, and on the other side, Clinton's supporters, known as Clintonians.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] In many districts, the remaining Federalists allied with the Clintonians, with candidates running on a joint ticket.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Several candidates who ran under that joint ticket cannot be clearly categorized, and are marked C/F.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Others who ran under the joint ticket are marked by their party with a footnote indicating that they ran under the joint ticket.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] North Carolina elected its members August 12, 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Ohio elected its members October 13, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Pennsylvania elected its members October 13, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Rhode Island elected its members August 25, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] South Carolina elected its members October 12–13, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] Tennessee elected its members August 5–6, 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] Vermont elected its members September 1, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] Virginia elected its members in April 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1819-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] There were four territories with the right to send non-voting delegates to at least part of the 16th Congress, two of which, Michigan Territory and Arkansas Territory were new to this Congress.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The **1820–21 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between July 3, 1820, and August 10, 1821.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 17th United States Congress convened on December 3, 1821.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] They coincided with President James Monroe winning reelection unopposed.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] In March 1820, seven House seats transferred from Massachusetts to Maine after the latter seceded from the former to become a separate state.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The size of the House then increased to 187 seats after Missouri achieved statehood in 1821.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The virtually nonpartisan Era of Good Feelings, a period of national political dominance by the Democratic-Republican Party, continued.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Despite small gains, the Federalist Party remained relegated to limited state and local influence.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] There were special elections in 1820 and 1821 to the 16th United States Congress and 17th United States Congress.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Alabama elected its member August 5–6, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Connecticut elected its members April 2, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Delaware elected its members October 3, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Georgia elected its members October 2, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Illinois elected its member August 7, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Indiana elected its member August 7, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Kentucky elected its members August 7, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Louisiana elected its member July 3–5, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] This was the first election in Maine since its separation from Massachusetts.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] In the previous election, Massachusetts had had 20 representatives.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Seven seats (representing the 14th-20th districts) were reassigned from Massachusetts to Maine.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] In addition, under the terms of the law which admitted Maine to the union, any vacancies in the 16th Congress by Representatives elected to represent Massachusetts but residing in the new states of Maine would be filled by a resident of Maine.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] John Holmes, who had been elected to the House for the former 14th district of Massachusetts was elected as one of the first two senators for Maine.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The vacancy was filled in a special election by Joseph Dane (Federalist).
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Dane was the only Representative officially considered as representing Maine in the 16th Congress.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The Representatives from the 15th-20th districts were still classified as being from Massachusetts for the remainder of the 16th Congress.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Maine elected its members on November 7, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] State law required a majority to win an election, necessitating additional ballots if a majority was not received.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] And, in fact, additional ballots were held on January 22, 1821, and September 10, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Maryland elected its members October 2, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] This was the first election in Massachusetts after the separation of the former District of Maine as the new State of Maine, taking the old 14th – 20th districts with it.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Massachusetts elected its members November 6, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Massachusetts had a majority requirement for election, which was not met in the 2nd district necessitating two additional elections on January 8, 1821, and April 16, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Mississippi elected its member August 7–8, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Missouri was admitted to the union on August 10, 1821, but elections had been held August 28, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] New Hampshire elected its members August 18, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] New Jersey elected its members November 7, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] There were an unusually large number of candidates, 119 candidates according to one contemporary newspaper.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Some candidates ran under an "Anti-Caucus" ticket.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Only 1 of the 6 six incumbents would serve in the next term, as 4 retired and 1 died after re-election.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] New York elected its members April 24–26, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The 21st district, previously a plural district with two seats, was divided into two single-member districts for the 17th Congress, the 21st and 22nd.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The Democratic-Republican party in New York was divided between "Bucktails" and "Clintonians".
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] The Clintonians ran on a joint ticket with the remaining Federalists.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] In a few cases, marked as "Clintonian/Federalist" below, it is unclear whether a candidate on the joint ticket was Democratic-Republican or Federalist.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Only five of the twenty-seven incumbents were re-elected to the next term.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Sixteen incumbents retired and five lost re-election.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] Despite this high turnover of membership, there was only a one-seat net gain for the Federalists.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p01] North Carolina elected its members August 9, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] Ohio elected its members October 10, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] Pennsylvania elected its members October 10, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] Rhode Island elected its members August 29, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] South Carolina elected its members October 9–10, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] Tennessee elected its members August 9–10, 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] In 1820, Vermont returned to using districts.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] This would be the only election in which the 6th district would be used.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] Vermont elected its members September 5, 1820.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] A majority was required for election, which was not met in the 2nd or 3rd district, requiring additional ballots to achieve a majority.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] The 3rd district required two additional ballots.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] The additional ballots were held December 11, 1820, and February 19, May 1, July 2, September 4, and October 22, 1821.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] Virginia elected its members in April 1821, after the term began but before the new Congress convened.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] There were four territories that had the right to send a delegate to at least part of the 17th Congress, only three of which actually sent delegates.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-illinois-p02] Missouri Territory's seat remained vacant, as the territory was admitted as the State of Missouri early in the 17th Congress.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] The **1820 United States presidential election in Illinois** took place between November 1 and December 6, 1820, as part of the 1820 United States presidential election.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] Voters chose three representatives, or electors, to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] It was the first presidential election that Illinois participated in since being admitted to the Union on December 3, 1818.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] Illinois cast three electoral votes for the Democratic-Republican candidate and incumbent President James Monroe, as he ran effectively unopposed.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] The electoral votes for vice president were cast for Monroe's running mate Daniel D.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1820-united-states-presidential-election-in-illinois] The state was divided into electoral districts with one elector each, and each district's voters chose the electors.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1852-chicago-mayoral-election] In the **1852 Chicago mayoral election**, incumbent Democrat Walter S.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1852-chicago-mayoral-election] Gurnee defeated former mayor James Curtiss (running as an independent) as well as Temperance candidate Amos G.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1852-chicago-mayoral-election] Throop and Mechanics candidate Peter Page by a ten-point margin.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1852-chicago-mayoral-election] Raymond was the initial nominee of the Temperance (Prohibition) Party.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1852-chicago-mayoral-election] However, for unspecified reasons, his candidacy was withdrawn in late February in favor of Throop.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1852-chicago-mayoral-election] The election was an energetic one, particularly due to the debate over liquor.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1852-chicago-mayoral-election] Other issues that were debated in the election were the reduction of taxes, avoiding an increase in city debt, preventing lawyers from obtaining gratuities, eliminating connection between the city government and private corporations, and suffrage.
[src:1852-chicago-mayoral-election/1852-chicago-mayoral-election] It was alleged during the campaign that a candidate in the previous election had spent $3,000 in buying voters liquor.
